^0^System Status
^$10
System Status 

Use System Status to find out basic information about your system.

You can do the following with System Status:

\to\t\k(Display System Information^^Displaying System Information)
\to\t\k(Change System Status Properties^^Changing System Status Properties)

^1^Displaying System Information
^$20
Displaying System Information

To display basic information about your system, do the following:

Note: If you are already in the Admin_Tools folder, go to Step 2.

1.\t\d(Double-click^double-click) on Admin_Tools in the \k("UnixWare Desktop" window^DesktopMgr/desktop.hlp^The UnixWare Desktop Window).
  \tThe "Folder: Admin_Tools" window appears.

2.\tDouble-click on System_Status. The "System Status" window appears with
  \tthe following information:

  \to\tThe version of UnixWare that your system is running (for example,
  \t \tUnixWare 2.0)

  \to\tThe Network node name (your system name)
 
  \to\tYour login id

  \to\tThe current date and time

  \to\tThe amount of system memory (RAM) installed

  \to\tThe type of math coprocessor chip installed, if your system has one.
  \t \tIf it does not have a coprocessor chip, the system displays the
  \t \tfollowing message at the bottom of the "System Status" window:
  \t \tno information available about math

  \to\tThe size and capacity of all the floppy disks, cartridge tape drives,
  \t \tCD-ROM drives, and so forth, on your system 

  \to\tThe total space of each file system

  \to\tThe amount of space the system is currently using 

  \to\tThe timezone

^1^Changing System Status Properties
^$30
Changing System Status Properties

You can change how often the system updates the clock and how often it
checks disk space.

In addition, if you have owner \k(permissions^dtadmin/user.hlp^Understanding Permissions) for administering accounts, you can
also change the system date, time, and timezone.

To change System Status properties, do the following:

Note: If you are already in the Admin_Tools folder, go to Step 2.

1.\t\d(Double-click^double-click) on Admin_Tools in the \k("UnixWare Desktop" window^DesktopMgr/desktop.hlp^The UnixWare Desktop Window).
  \tThe "Folder: Admin_Tools" window appears.

2.\tDouble-click on System_Status. The "System Status" window appears with

3.\tClick on Actions=>Properties. The "System Status: Properties"
  \twindow appears.

  \tIf you are not the system owner, you will see only the following
  \ttwo fields:

  \to\tupdate clock every - Type in (in seconds) how often you want
  \t \tthe system to update the clock in the "System Status" window.

  \to\tcheck disks every - Type in (in seconds) how often you want the
  \t \tsystem to check the hard disk for available space.

  \tIf you are the system owner, you can change the two fields described
  \tabove, as well as the system date, time, and timezone. Use the arrow
  \tkeys next to each box (or type in the value) for year, month, day, hour
  \t(using a 24-hour clock), minute, and timezone.

  \tNote: When you select timezone, the system first prompts you to choose
  \tthe continent (for example, North America or Europe).

  \tAfter you click on the desired name, the system then prompts you for the
  \tactual timezone. For example, if you choose North America, the system
  \tprompts you for Eastern, Central, Mountain, and so forth. If you choose
  \tEurope, the system prompts you for Great Britain, Central Europe,
  \tWestern Europe, and so forth.

4.\tClick OK to make the changes.

  \tNote: If you want to go back to default values, click on Set Defaults.


 

